HEADWORD: Renovation
<hw>Ren`o**va"tion</hw> <pr>(-v?"sh?n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>renovatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>r⟦eacute⟧novation</ets>.]</ety>
<def>The act or process of renovating; the state of being renovated or
renewed.</def> <rj><au>Thomson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is something inexpressibly pleasing in the annual
<qex>renovation</qex> of the world.</q> <rj><qau>Rabbler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Renovator</ent>⟦br⟧
